Si tiene preguntas sobre el programa o no ha recibido un beneficio, el Navegador de Asistencia al Estudiante ESD 113 está disponible para brindar apoyo a las familias del distrito escolar de Rochester. Si desea ayuda, llame al 360-858-1940 para hablar con el navegador. Las reuniones en persona y de Zoom están disponibles con cita previa. Todas las reuniones en persona se llevarán a cabo en Rochester High School. Quienes se reúnan en persona deberán seguir los protocolos del distrito vigentes para prevenir y controlar la propagación de COVID-19, incluido el uso de una máscara y tomarse la temperatura cuando ingrese al edificio. "

post_text: The P-EBT program deadline has been extended to Sept 11th. If you receive Free or Reduced Price Meals or SNAP benefits, you are automatically eligible for P-EBT. If you have questions about the program or haven't received a benefit, the ESD 113 Student Assistance Navigator is available to provide support to Rochester school district families . If you would like assistance please call at 360-858-1940 to speak to the Navigator. In-person and Zoom meetings are available by appointment. All in-person meetings will be at Rochester High School. Those meeting in person will need to follow the district protocols in place to prevent and control the spread of COVID-19, including wearing a mask and taking your temperature when you enter the building. "

As we continue to grieve the loss of Justin Rotter, an exceptional man, teacher and coach, we wanted to share a resource to give our students and staff an opportunity to talk through this challenging experience.

Rochester High School will have ESD 113 counselors available on Monday, July 27th from 10:00-2:00 if you would like to talk with someone about this difficult situation. There will be counselors available for person to person conversations as well as counselors available for Zoom conversations, phone calls, or FaceTime. If you would like to talk to someone face to face, please wear a mask and be ready for a series of questions regarding your health and a temperature check at the front door of RHS If you would prefer a Zoom meeting, a phone call or a FaceTime conversation, please call 360-523-4735 to set up a time.

If meeting at Rochester High School will not work for you, the District Office can be an alternative location to meet with a counselor. Please call 360-523-4735 if that is a better option for you.

It is with overwhelming sadness that RSD confirms that RHS math teacher and coach, Justin Rotter, passed away on Friday, July 24th due to an unforeseen medical emergency. He was 44 years old.
Mr. Rotter graduated from Rochester High School in 1994, graduated from WSU and spent his entire 19 year teaching career serving in the community he loved.
Mr. Rotter was an exemplary educator, coach, mentor, colleague, friend and family man. He is truly deserving of the title - WARRIOR!
We ask that you keep his family, co-workers, and past and present students in your thoughts and prayers.

post_text:
The Rochester School Board of Directors took action last night to name Mike Smith as the next principal of HEART and Rochester High schools. Mr. Smith has served as a high school administrator in the North Thurston School District for the last 11 years, and worked as a teacher of students with emotional and behavioral disabilities prior to becoming an administrator.

When asked about a goal he has for his work in Rochester Mr. Smith stated, “My goal would be to make secondary education personally and culturally meaningful for every student. I feel that a student's educational programming should prepare them for their next stage in life, whether that is to prepare them for college/university, trade school, military, or directly into the workforce. I want to ensure every student has guidance, support, and the academic skill sets needed to be successful.”

Mr. Smith will join Rochester School District on July 1, 2020. Special thanks to all the students and parents who provided feedback during the hiring process.

Three Updates for RSD Families
1. Due to the Governor's extension of the Stay Home, Stay Healthy Declaration, our schools are now scheduled to reopen Tuesday, May 5th.
2. Free meals will continue to be delivered next week, even though it's our scheduled spring break.
3. Monday is the day we'll distribute our first printed work packets. They'll arrive at bus stops along with the free meals. Printed work packets are only for those families who have limited or no Internet or extenuating circumstances, AND who have communicated their need for a packet to their child's teacher or school. Bus stops and ESTIMATED bus delivery times are available on the district website. http://www.rochester.wednet.edu/parent__student_resources/bus_routes
We're all WARRIORS, and we'll get through this together!
Stay well!

Rochester School District will continue to be available to support our students. Office staff and administrators will be checking voicemail and email messages daily; however, we will be closing all our offices beginning Friday, March 20 to keep our staff healthy and to fully participate in the effort to slow the spread of COVID-19.
Key personnel have been identified who will be working to ensure continuity of services, such as the distribution of meals and Chromebooks, providing technical support and essential district operations during the COVID-19 closure. We have implemented telecommuting options for all eligible staff, including our teachers, who will be reaching out to families soon. Parents/guardians are encouraged to check the district website at www.rochester.wednet.edu regularly for resources and updates.

SCHOOL CLOSURE ANNOUNCEMENT:
All Schools in Rochester School District, and throughout Thurston County, will be closed March 16-April 24 to slow the spread of COVID-19. There will be no school activities, including sports, or community use of district facilities during the closure.
School Messenger notifications containing additional information have gone out to families. We are currently in the process of developing district plans to support students with non-educational services as requested by the Governor and OSPI. The first service to become operational will be meals for students, which we anticipate occurring as early as Tuesday.

Further communication regarding these services will be forthcoming. Please check the district website www.rochester.wednet.edu for today’s notification to families and for future updates.

post_text:
COVID-19 Update 3-12-20 2:25 PM

Rochester School District is aware of the rapidly changing nature of COVID-19 in our state, including the first confirmed case in Thurston County, and the Governor's directive to close schools in Snohomish, King, and Pierce Counties for six (6) weeks.

The rest of the state will continue to be closely monitored, and the Governor will expand school closures to other counties if warranted based on the spread of the virus, the rates of confirmed cases, and staff and student attendance.

In the meantime, Rochester School District will continue to follow the guidance of the Thurston County Health Department and will immediately contact families via School Messenger if a decision is made to close our schools.

To that end, we’ve met with a representative from the Washington State Department of Health (DOH), and are also regularly accessing guidance and resources from the National Center for Disease Control (CDC) and the Office of the Superintendent of Public Instruction (OSPI). Rochester School District will follow all official guidance as it is updated.

Below is a link to more information http://www.rochester.wednet.edu/news/what_s_new/coronavirus_information

January 29th, 5-7 pm - RHS Library

RHS is hosting a scholarship workshop on January 29th from 5-7 pm in the library. Tyler Kaut from CC will be here to help everyone apply for the CC Scholarship. The plan is to have applications submitted before leaving. In order to do this, those attending will have to have already applied to Centralia College and received their student ID and student email. That process is simple but has to be done by January 23rd to ensure you receive the new student info in time.

If you are even slightly considering CC as an option for next year, just apply and come to the workshop...you might be surprised and receive a great scholarship that will help you make up your mind. The link for applying is below.

You are welcome to come to the counseling center if you need additional assistance as well.

post_text:
UPDATE: Thanks to your help, the district connected with a new representative from the Department of Transportation (DOT) and we're making great progress. Although safety improvements to the crosswalks in front of RMS do not qualify for DOT funding at this time, DOT staff will install flashing beacons if the district purchases them. It will take about three months for the equipment to arrive and be installed. We wish it could happen sooner, but we are grateful this safety improvement will be made. In the meantime, a new hand-held flashing stop paddle has been purchased for our crossing guard to use.
Thanks again for your advocacy for the safety of Rochester students!
text:

Although safety improvements to the crosswalks in front of RMS do not qualify for DOT funding at this time, DOT staff will install flashing beacons if the district purchases them. It will take about three months for the equipment to arrive and be installed. We wish it could happen sooner, but we are grateful this safety improvement will be made. In the meantime, a new hand-held flashing stop paddle has been purchased for our crossing guard to use.
Thanks again for your advocacy for the safety of Rochester students!

post_text:
Join us in wearing organge today to STAND UP AGAINST BULLYING! Here are four things we can all do:
TAKE NOTICE: Pay attention to situations in which you see a fellow student being bullied or harmed.
TAKE ACTION: Standing by, or silently laughing along, helps encourage bullying. If you can, try to help a child or teen who is being bullied find a way out.
BE KIND: Reach out and connect with any of your peers who might feel left out. A simple “hello” can make all the difference in someone’s life.
SPEAK UP: Tell a trusted adult if you see a child or teen who is being bullied. Ask for help.

post_text: Did you know the National School Lunch/Breakfast Program requires a new application every year? A 30-day grace period is extended to all students who received free or reduced priced meals last year to give their parents/guardians time to complete a new form. Applications are available in all school offices and online at https://rochester.wednet.edu/cms/one.aspx?pageId=550469

August 29, 2019 at 11:24 AM ·

Back to School Bash is happening next Friday, September 6th, from 5-7pm at Grand Mound Elementary! All RPS and GMES families are welcome to attend this exciting event. Enjoy some free food, resources, giveaways, prizes, and a magic show with Jeff Evans! Look for our fliers, and feel free to share this post to friends and families. See you there!

RHS ROBOTICS DUO HEADED TO NATIONAL COMPETITION

Angelica Pipo and Kyler Clark took first place in the State Skills USA Robotics Urban Search & Rescue competition, earning the opportunity to competing for a national title in Louisville, Kentucky on June 24-27.

If you’d like to make a donation to help off-set the students’ travel expenses you can do so online at https://wa-rochester.intouchreceipting.com or by dropping by the Rochester School District Office.

PROM is just around the corner! PROM 2019 - Light Up The Night - will be held in the TAC on the Centralia College campus. Doors open at 8:00pm and the dance ends at 11:00pm. Desserts and refreshments will be served.

Music requests must be made PRIOR to the dance. A request list is posted on Ms. Morris’ window. If there are songs you’d like played, please get them listed by WED May 1st!

Guest passes are available at the main office. They are due May 1st. Turn them in to Ms. Morris.

Finally, Tickets are $20 each. See Ms. Morris at the Cashiers window during lunches! Questions? See Mrs. Thomas in room 103.

This event is sponsored and hosted by the Centralia College Teaching Program and student teachers currently in this program will be running stations of math games.
The objective will be to help model good questioning strategies for families as they play games with their children.
Students will receive a ticket when they enter that will be stamped at each game station. When all stations are complete they can turn in their ticket for a bag of popcorn.
Students, families and any staff that choose to come are encouraged to wear Sports Themed attire!

post_text: On Saturday, February 2, the Rochester High School CTE program hosted the regional Urban Search and Rescue Robotics competition in the STEM lab. Eighteen students from Rochester High School, Aberdeen High School, and Elma Middle & High School competed. The competition was successful and many family members attended in support of the students. Rochester robotics students took high honors, placing 1st and 2nd overall. The winning team consisted of Brycen Horner and Aspen Williams. In second place was Derek Letteer and Brandon Davis. Congratulations to the winning teams and to all the students and families for their hard work and time put into preparing for this competition! Teams will be starting to prepare for the state competition in April. Students are pictured with their CTE teacher Mr. Paul Kuss.

post_text: This is the time of year that we tend to see an increase in the number of individuals diagnosed with pertussis (whooping cough). So far this year there have been numerous suspected, probable and confirmed cases reported in Thurston County. The Thurston County Health Department has notified us that Pertussis was identified in two Rochester High School students over break. Both have been treated and are no longer contagious. While typically a relatively mild illness for older children and adults, pertussis can be life threatening for infants and young children, and dangerous for pregnant women. This is a reminder to keep your child home if they are ill. If they are coughing, please have them evaluated by their health care provider.

The RHS Basketball Cheerleaders invite K thru 8th grade students to register for the opportunity to perform at the Warriors basketball game for a Warrior Holiday Halftime Cheer Performance.

There will be two days of practice at GMES Cafeteria from 3:30-5 pm on December 19th and December 20th

Cost of Clinic and Performance: $40.00 (Make payable to RHS)

Register by 12/18/2018 https://docs.google.com/document/d/1baWSdSaCroEwaliTdmP-3L-XD0oP3rEJHDOdtuBpzkg/edit?usp=sharing

Return payment and registration form to Ms. Morris at RHS or PAY ONLINE. https://wa-rochester.intouchreceipting.com/

Cost includes performance t-shirt and antlers.
